ive hour set, using SolSt1ne\u2019s emphasis on signal quality rather than raw conviction alone.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- In the surviving `11/12/20` and `v5a_pass` sample:\n  - `55-64.9` band: `6` trades, MACD abs avg `9.697`\n    - winners MACD abs avg `11.238`\n    - loser MACD abs avg `1.994`\n  - `65-80` band: `3` trades, MACD abs avg `9.565`\n    - lone winner MACD abs `18.616`\n    - losers MACD abs avg `5.040`\n- So average MACD across the two bands is similar overall, but **the winners consistently have much stronger MACD than the losers**, especially in the extreme-bias bucket.\n- This matches SolSt1ne\u2019s broader lesson: signal quality matters more than raw score magnitude.\n\n**My thinking:**\nI\u2019m more convinced now that the high-bias issue is not \u201cextreme bias bad.\u201d It is \u201cextreme bias without strong momentum confirmation is dangerous.\u201d That is a much better research direction than fiddling with the bias cap alone. If we ever tighten this logic, MACD-strength gating inside the upper bias band is the more credible lever.\n\n**Decision:*",
